<div id="stitle" style="display:none;">Notebook Entry</div>
<dl id="n09152m"> <dt class="nbunit"><a name="n09" href="#n09152m">N09 (VI.B.1)</a>:  <a href="../../FF/fnbs/n09all.htm#n09152m"> 152(m)</a></dt> <dd> <blockquote> scandal of Livingstone</blockquote> <dd class="well"> <blockquote class="sources">This surprise of Stanley&apos;s is all part and parcel of the African story. Down around Zanzibar the &ldquo;east of Suez&rdquo; sort had stuffed him with the usual <mark>lies about</mark> &ldquo;the idol.&rdquo; (1) That <mark>Livingstone</mark> possessed a splenetic, misanthropic temper. (2) That he was garrulous and demented. (3) That he was utterly changed from the David Livingstone whom people knew as the reverend missionary, (4) With not too feeble attempt to be evasive&mdash;the usual &ldquo;black woman&rdquo; insinuation. <small> Dan Crawford, <a name="BTLG1" href="../../FF/fdra/fdex.htm#BTLG1"><cite title="source">Back to the Long Grass</cite></a> (1923) 116f</small></blockquote> <mm class="note">Note: David Livingstone (1813-1873): Scottish missionary and explorer in Africa.</mm> </dd></dl>
